column7: It seems to me that highly specific guidelines here will likely lead to a quagmire of interpretation challenges.  There are so many subtly different circumstances involved that rules that speak of specific distances will either be unusable, or will be used in ways contrary to the original intent.  As well, some of the guidelines mentioned seem to be more supportive of 'traffic' trying to get through a neighbourhood (and, therefore, not really contributing to it) than of the street life of the neighbourhood (which, imho, is more important, and is the benefit of buskers in the first place).  I find myself wondering how much of a problem we actually have with inappropriate busking, and whether we're trying to avoid problems that we don't actually have (or that only certain people have, or that could be addressed in ways less harmful to street life).

Regulating buskers is a thankless task. All those rules about so many metres from here and so many meters from there are just crazy-making ideas. My delightful busker may be your busker-from-hell.  

Perhaps we need a simpler more self-managing scheme:

Think of this: 

-Every busker must have a city designed app on a smart phone.
-The app would:
   -allow busker to buy a desired amount of busking time per day.
   -monitor their precise location
   -green-light busking for a limited period at a given location, then
   -issue a red-light alert to the busker when purchased time is up, or
when time-at-current location is exceeded, or busking at a prohibited location is occuring, or number-of-buskers-at-a-location exceeds regulations (first-in buskers are protected at a location until their time-at-location is up or their total time  is up.)

Any peace officer can ask to see a busker's app. If it is red-lighted, the busker gets a ticket.)

Of course with an app, fines could be automatically charged to a busker's account (and be paid automatically from the busker's on-file credit card.)

Fines would be charged at an growing scale as the time in the red zone increases. 

Thank you.

There are vanishingly few sites that meet this criteria in most of the commercial areas where such activity would likely be centred (e.g. Whyte Ave).  Forcing smokers and buskers to fight for these limited spots is counterproductive and likely to result in resentment and/or non-compliance in many circumstances.

Some businesses may have an ideal spot for a busker to set up, and may even welcome such activity.  Forcing the busker to move from these spots is again counterproductive, and contrary to the stated goal of making busking a positive experience.  

Should a business decide that they do not want a busker near their entrance, they should be able to ask them to move at least 5 m away, but it should not be a mandatory distance.

With alley way entrances, again this would depend on the site.  There are many alley ways where ideal sites for busking would be located in close proximity to an alley (such as in the parking lot of a business, especially if the business is closed).  10 meters is also an extremely large buffer for an alley.  Vehicles should not be entering or moving through an alley at greater than 20 kph in any circumstances.  3 m would be a more appropriate buffer distance.

Most boulevard situations would need to have buskers on the inside "track", but in some areas there may be sidewalks with large enough boulevards that busking could be allowed there.  Hopefully future developments, with more emphasis on walking promenades and the like will have more room for such activities.  The bylaw should not have such an ingrained arbitrary bias.  Perhaps a minimum width of the busking area would be a better measure (e.g. at least 2 m).

column7: Moving a problem doesn't fix it. column7: On busy main streets, based on the separation distances, where would busking be allowed?

First you need a definition of busker.  The guidelines defined will effectively eliminate busker and the creativity and life they bring to the street and public. If they need to be 5 m from a business entrance, 15 m from a controlled intersection, 10 m from an alley there is no place they could be on the inside or outside of the sidewalk that would comply with this type of bylaw.

Instead, the City should designate suitable locations on every block for buskers and perhaps (as they do at the farmer's market) have them audition to provide street entertainment.  The City and/or local business association could administrate this and rotate the locations weekly and the performers daily so that no one business has them parked outside continually. Perhaps the City should also provide a stipend to support buskers who enliven the street (LRT station or other public squares) and add entertainment and atmosphere.   

There should be bylaws that limit the decibel level so that excessive sound is not an issue. There also should be safety considerations for buskers to prevent theft.  Perhaps at each location there could be a locked box for public to put change into.

Lets not sterilize our streets and prevent them from being alive with all kinds of activity.

The concern I have is if you take these proposed guidelines together, then there may be areas where no busking can occur.  While I'm not necessarily against that, there could be an uproar and the guidelines could be shot down even though there are good reasons for them (like the cannabis smoking guidelines - which were changed the next day because it appears those with vices have a louder and more important voice than those who want to be able to breathe fresh air).

column7:
Most of the Buskers I have seen have blocked or were extremely close to entrances of local businesses which often hindered local business or to its patrons.  This is not acceptable behavior especially when the Busker has been asked to move.  I am mostly speaking of restaurants, lounges, and bars which try to create an experience to the establishment whereby the Busker's musical performance does not coincide with the establishment.  Some musically inclined Buskers are very good while others are not and does create altercations with businesses as this affects whether or not a patron will enter the establishment.  As well, I have seen Buskers get into arguments over their "space" on the sidewalk which has also led to some bloody altercations.  Considerations should be made for local businesses as the Buskers can hinder or enhance the patrons entering their establishment.  As well, to eliminate the chance of altercations between Buskers, an amendment should be made regarding the distance between Buskers.  To put forth a scenario which did happen on Whyte Avenue with an open air restaurant playing classical background music and had two musically inclined Buskers in close proximity to the restaurant.  Both claimed "space" on the block with one playing Bongo drums and the other playing a guitar singing country and western music.  These two Buskers began a competition to outdo the other in volume.  The restaurant manager asked the Buskers to either tone down or leave as this was affecting the restaurant.  An argument ensued and the police were called.  Perhaps an amendment is required to limit the same type of Buskers performing on each street.  For example, you can have a mime, stilt walker, and musician/singer on one block but not more than one type on each block performing at the same time.  The same would go for the LRT stations as there are several Buskers there as well.

I would suggest contacting the City of Vancouver or the City of Toronto or checking their websit

column7: Keep busking to an absolute minimum. Prioritize pedestrian traffic. Ideally busking should be kept to small off-sidewalk areas and small parks (such as by the old Strathcona Farmer's market)
I enjoy busking but do worry about the safety and noise portions.
Sometimes too many rules and guidelines make it difficult to monitor.  Will bylaw be around handing out tickets?  Have there been issues before?  Why the new rules?
They should not take place on a busy road.

All the distances seem excessive and I can't think of any reason why a busker would need to be 10 meters from an ally entrance or 15 meters from an intersection.

And while I understand the need to keep buskers from blocking doors and entrances to residences and businesses, 3 meters seems more than adequate. As well, I also feel that the distance guidelines should only apply to entrances of open businesses. (E.g. if a clothing store closes at 5 P.M. on a Saturday, there doesn't seem to be a compelling reason to prevent buskers from performing within 5 meters of that stores entrance later in the evening.)

I think busking is harmless and provides entertainment and a moment of joy for passersby.  I think the guidelines are fair.

*** The buskers are not really the problem, the problem are the people at major intersections who hold signs saying they are homeless, or jobless, or hungry.  It's a safety hazard and sometimes the people are polite but sometimes they will approach your car asking for money.  This is a big problem.
There is always someone at the 23ave and 91st intersection.  And at the 34ave and 99st intersection.  A large group of people rotate and are always there asking for money.  Can you please address this problem?  Can you send someone from the city to help them?  Help them connect with an organization that can help them.  It's sad.  I see young people, old people, middle aged people.  There are men and women who need help.  It's sad and my kids are always asking me for money to give them, they really get distressed by seeing them asking for money.

15 meters from this and 10 meters from that basically makes every spot along a busy commercial street illegal but that is the very spot where busking makes sense both for buskers and business owners and street shoppers. Quiet streets 15 meters away from an intersection and 5 meters from any door to or from any business is a terrible place to busk.

It sounds as though the city is trying to make life as difficult as possible for buskers with these proposals. Buskers depend on proximity to businesses for audience, and I doubt many spots count be found that are 5 m away from businesses AND 15 meters away from intersections AND 10 meters away from alleys.

It all seems like a bit of an over-reach that aims to solve a problem that I wasn't aware was that large at the cost of stripping away some heart and fun of a city. My view of people who complain about buskers is to move to the suburbs - that's what life in a big city is all about - occasional noise and crowding.
